content:
Creating a chessboard on a web page using JavaScript is a fun project. You can achieve this by using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Here's a simple way to create a chessboard where each cell is 50x50 pixels:

### HTML
First, set up a basic HTML structure with a `<div>` where the chessboard will be drawn.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Chessboard</title>
    <style>
        #chessboard {
            display: grid;
            grid-template-columns: repeat(8, 50px);
            grid-template-rows: repeat(8, 50px);
            width: 400px;
            height: 400px;
        }
        .black {
            background-color: black;
        }
        .white {
            background-color: white;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="chessboard"></div>
    <script src="chessboard.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### JavaScript
Next, create the `chessboard.js` file to generate the chessboard:

```javascript
function drawChessboard() {
    const chessboard = document.getElementById('chessboard');

    for (let row = 0; row < 8; row++) {
        for (let col = 0; col < 8; col++) {
            const cell = document.createElement('div');

            // Determine the color of the cell
            if ((row + col) % 2 === 0) {
                cell.classList.add('white');
            } else {
                cell.classList.add('black');
            }

            chessboard.appendChild(cell);
        }
    }
}

// Call the function to draw the chessboard when the page loads
window.onload = drawChessboard;
```

### Explanation
- **HTML**: The `<div>` with the id `chessboard` serves as the container for our chessboard.
- **CSS**: We use CSS Grid to create an 8x8 grid where each cell is 50x50 pixels. We define styles for `.black` and `.white` classes to color the cells appropriately.
- **JavaScript**: The function `drawChessboard()` creates 64 `<div>` elements (8 rows and 8 columns). It uses a simple check `(row + col) % 2 === 0` to alternate between black and white cells, appending each cell to the chessboard container.

This setup will render a chessboard on your web page with each cell sized at 50x50 pixels.
